    {
      "id": "074b8850_8d392888",
      "file_path": "models-tosca/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/models/tosca/authorative/concepts/ToscaCapabilityAssignment.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 42,
      "message": "I'm just thinking a little more about what \"equality\" means in terms of TOSCA entities. Should two things with the same name and version but with other differences be considered \"equal\"? Instinctively I think the answer to that should be no, so I think maybe we're misusing the concept of equality here.\n\nLet's discuss at the scrum tomorrow.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2787,
        "name": "Liam Fallon",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
        "username": "liamfallon"
      },
      "updated": "2020-11-30 20:07:10.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "42010031_6a5d246c",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "a9a95a75_01136957",
      "file_path": "models-tosca/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/models/tosca/authorative/concepts/ToscaCapabilityAssignment.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 42,
      "message": "we have sprint planning tomorrow, but can discuss it briefly.\n\nbasically, the \"consistent with equals\" contract is that compareTo() should only return 0 if equals() returns true, and goes on to say that it's dangerous to do otherwise.  Of course, if equals() is implemented, then it should work with arbitrary objects so that it can be used to identify matching items in a List<Object>.  And if equals() is implemented, then hashCode() should typically be implemented.\n\nOTOH, maybe compareTo() isn't needed at all?  sort() methods take a comparison method, so any method can be used there and they don't need to be \"consistent with equals\".  The same is true (i.e., a comparison method can be provided) in the unlikely event that one of these objects is used as a KEY in an ordered set/map, and compareTo isn't needed at all for unordered sets/maps (e.g., HashSet).\n\nIf we can't do one or the other of the above, then perhaps we should name the method something other than compareTo.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2020-11-30 20:38:00.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "074b8850_8d392888",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "7a38cb9e_e2805d74",
      "file_path": "models-tosca/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/models/tosca/authorative/concepts/ToscaCapabilityAssignment.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 42,
      "message": "I took a different approach using comparators, I think it is better not to interfere with the natural order of things :-)",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2787,
        "name": "Liam Fallon",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
        "username": "liamfallon"
      },
      "updated": "2020-12-01 12:51:14.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "a9a95a75_01136957",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "id": "5c7f0237_a9a53f4b",
      "file_path": "models-tosca/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/models/tosca/authorative/concepts/ToscaPolicyComparator.java",
      "patchset_number": 3,
      "line": 33,
      "message": "I could not get the Collections.sort(collection, Comparator<T>) method to accept a comparator for the super types of ToscaPolicy and ToscaPolicyType (that is PfNameVersion), it seems Java does not allow a comparator of a superclass of the type being compared. Anyhow, these comparator classes are tiny so it's not a big deal.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2787,
        "name": "Liam Fallon",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
        "username": "liamfallon"
      },
      "updated": "2020-12-01 12:51:14.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": true
    },
